<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission to the Culture, Media and Sport Select Committee inquiry into the Future of the BBC</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.5pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Pact [FBB0080]</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pact is the UK trade association representing and promoting the commercial interests of independent feature film, television, digital, children's and animation media companies.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The UK independent television sector is one of the biggest in the world. Despi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">te the difficult economic climate, independent television sector revenues have grown from £1.3 billion in 2005 to nearly £2.8 billion in 2012.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2012, the BBC spent £507 million on commissions from UK independent producers. This was an increase from £4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">37m in 2011</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The BBC commissioned 36% (37% in 2011-12) of eligible television content from external producers</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BBC Commissions are important for independent producers as they account for 33% of all UK commissions, making the BBC the biggest buyer of con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tent made by independent producers in the UK.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pact is a supporter of the licence fee and recognises the important role that the BBC plays in British broadcasting. The BBC is also a leader on the world stage in terms of public services broadcasting. Howeve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r, Pact highlights a number of areas in the submission where improvements could be made. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">uture of the BBC inquiry</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pact is a supporter of the BBC and the licence fee, re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cognising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that it plays an important role in terms of both value</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to the UK economy and culture and promoting the British brand overseas. Removing or reducing the licence fee in any way could have negative repercussions for the broadcasting sector.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In terms of the BBC achieving against its public purposes, Pact would l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ike to see improvements in number of areas:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">On promoting education and learning, the BBC children’s programming budget should be further protected from cost savings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s achievement with the nations and regions is progressing well according to the latest figures. This progress is welcome and Pact will continue to monitor the situation. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Work on diversity could go further, to ensure that the BBC truly reflects th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e lives, aspirations and cultures of a diverse country</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With regard to emerging communications technologies, the BBC’s investment of £100m through its Digital Media Initiative earlier in the year did not ultimately deliver any benefits to the BBC or the b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">roader industry. Pact would like to see the future focus of digital development on developing new technologies in partnership with companies already investing in solutions.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Beyond 2016, Pact would like to see mor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e of the BBC licence fee </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">invested in conten</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC should become a publisher/ broadcaster. The WoCC (Window of Creative Competition) should not act as a cap on external commissions and the BBC should opt for the best programme regardless of whether this is produced in-house or by an independen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t producer (excluding news).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pact supports the licence fee in order to fund the BBC beyond 2016. The licence fee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is one of the key drivers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">creation of intellectual property in the UK which can then be exploited overseas, creating and sustaining tho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">usands of jobs within the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">broadcasting industry. Any redistribution of the licence fee </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would seriously erode the ability of the BBC to act as a corner stone of excellence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Such a move would limit its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risk taking without any de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">monstrable benefits to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all UK broadcasting ecology.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Response to the Inquiry questions</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Mission and purpose</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What should the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">How well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period in achieving its mission and public purposes? </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Are the public purposes in the current Charter the right ones? How might they change?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The purpose of the BBC and public service television broadcasting should be to create excellent and innovative content across a range of programme genres. It should act as a benchmark for the commercial sector by setting the creative standard for other PSB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and commercial channels in the UK and increasingly abroad.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC must continue to take risks and invest in drama, comedy and entertainment; taking risks that may be more difficult for commercial broadcasters. This helps to identify new talent that the w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hole industry benefits from. The BBC must also maintain its world-class reputation for factual content.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pact is a supporter of the BBC and the licence fee, recognising that the BBC brings both economic benefits to the UK economy and influence or ‘soft powe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r’ as part of its role in promoting the British brand overseas. The benefits attached to the licence fee are reflected in the value of the services provided and the wider economic benefit to the UK.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC is an integral part of UK life and its editorial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">output is an important part of British culture and society. Any policy which diminishes the licence fee further could result in the loss of a number of positive multiplier effects. The BBC and other PSBs set broadcasting standards for other media channels </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the UK and worldwide. Arguably, this is positive for UK creativity and innovation in the wider creative industries too. Quality PSB programming is clearly something that UK audiences appreciate hence the significant investments by Cable and Satellite ch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">annels into high quality original programming that is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> often indistinguishable from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that provided by licensed PSB channels.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In terms of achieving its mission and public purposes, the BBC has performed well against its public purposes over</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the current Charte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r period. With regard to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘sustaining citizenship and civil society’, the BBC should continue its excellence in coverage of news and current affairs and factual programming. On ‘stimulating cultural creativity and excellence’, it should continue to inspire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">creativity, innovation and talent across a range of genres. On ‘bringing the UK to the world and the world to the UK’, we will touch on in the submission the value of the BBC overseas and the increase in TV exports.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The current public purposes remain broad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly well targeted but Pact would like to see improvements in the following areas:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Promoting education and learning</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The recent BBC Trust Review of Children’s Services report revealed that funding for children’s programming has not been ring fenced and faces </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">budget cuts. In this regard, it is concerning that the BBC has emerged as the last </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dominant investor and buyer of children’s programming over recent years, with ITV and Channel 4 playing a noticeably lesser role in this space.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In light of this, the Governm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ent should, on the back of the success of tax credits for film, high end TV and animation, look into providing appropriate fiscal incentives to support children’s programming into the future. Investment in children’s programming is important in developing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and sustaining British culture and language and a generation of viewers that will enjoy content from the BBC and public service broadcasters into the future.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Since the publication of the BBC Trust report, Pact is engaged in further discussions with the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> around improving communication and transparency in the commissioning process and also investigating future funding options for children’s programming, for example, through collaboration with other channels.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Representing the nations, regions, communities</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pact will continue to the monitor the BBC’s progress towards the target of realising 50% of network television by spend, outside London, by 2016. This target, set by the BBC Trust, includes 17% to be spent in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland respective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly. We are pleased to see that the BBC is on schedule to achieve this with 46% of spend achieved out of London and just under 16% in the devolved countries. The progress made on out of London spend will help contribute towards the sustained and organic gro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wth of the sector across the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In terms of diversity, BBC programming content should reflect the diversity of licence fee payers in England and across the devolved countries. It seems that there is still further work to do in terms of appealing to viewe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rs in lower income brackets and particularly the 16-24 age range within that. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Delivering the benefits of emerging communications technologies</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pact is plea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sed that IPlayer has emerged as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a world standard for IPTV (Internet Protocol TV) that other UK channe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ls and broadcasters globally are keen to emulate. Pact recognises the volume of investment that was injected into fully realising this project.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pact is keen that any future projects tapping into new technologies should be developed in collaboration with the industry and not separately. We expand on this theme later in the submission. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Scope, scale and remit</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What scope, scale and remit should the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">BBC have?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Should the BBC</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">s output and services be provided to any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences? What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to create?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1 The k</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ey issue for Pact is, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">what </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is an appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">balance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">trike </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">between production in-house and external commissions. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pact would reiterate the point made in previous submissions that the BBC should primarily be a publisher-broadcaster (apa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rt from the news</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which should be retained). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">All demand for programming could be filled and supplied by the market, driving efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> savings in the BBC,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> releasing more funds to invest in high quality content and providing other benefits to the broader UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Television industry.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Beyond Charter Renewal in 2016, Pact would like to see more funding released to the wider supply market. We would like to see the BBC always </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">opt for the best programme regardless </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of who the supplier is. This will ensure th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at the BBC focusses on securing the best ideas at the best price from the market and the market will absorb the costs that currently are met by the BBC servicing a large fixed cost base of personnel and facilities.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.4 The BBC can easily</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ensure continuity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of supply by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">entering into long running agreements as it currently does for a number of key programming strands such as Question Time and Waterloo Road made by an Independent and non </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Independent production company respectively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.5 Adopting a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">publisher/ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">broadcaster approach could have the potential of a ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">big bang</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’ effect and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contribute to the further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">development of the UK TV industry. This would be good for the market overall, creating savings for the BBC and far from displacing talent, it would release t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">alent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that could be utilised by the BBC, other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PSBs and commercial broadcasters driving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">competitio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n and innovation.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.6 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Licence fee payers will continue to demand more value, more quality and more options in the future. BBC ratings show that top I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ndie shows are amongst the most popular e.g. Sherlock, Master Chef, The Voice and others. In 2012, UK Indies won half of all TV Baftas (12 out of 24).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.7 The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BBC is well placed to meet the needs of licence fee payers but to do so it has to ensure that it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s primary focus is on delivering the most creative, high quality programming that they can provid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e while driving down the BBC's </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cost base in order to continue to invest in original UK content across all genres.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">How have the BBC</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">s commercial activities dur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ing the current Charter fitted with the BBC</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">s public purposes and have they achieved an adequate return for licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale of such activities beyond 2016?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.6 BBC Worldwide from the BBC’s commercial arm is an i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mportant distributor of content. Looking to the future, BBC Worldwide should remain focused, based on its current remit and continue to operate as trading body at arms length. Its operations should remain clear and commercially transparent. Potentially, by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> opening up opportunities through the WoCC, BBC Worldwide could have more opportunities as the distributor of a broader rights base.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Developing technology</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Graf Report published in 2005, reviewed BBC online and set out that the BBC had failed to use the licence fee to support the digital production sector. Opportunities were not taken at the time and issues were raised around external commissioning.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 16.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">me ways, eight years later the position has not sufficiently improved. </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is still work to do in creating a fully 21</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> century digital production sector. Pact’s submission to the BBC Trust’s Online Service review outlined concerns, amongst others, aroun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 34.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The fact that the online quota is largely met by commissioning several pieces of low value content and services from many different external suppliers. This suggests outsourcing is happening rather than a genuine investment by the BBC on content, servic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es and technology from external suppliers</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 34.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The decision made by the BBC Executive not to introduce a digital WoCC, allowing independent producers to access more opportunities beyond the 25% quota.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.3 Pact would be sceptical about future attempts made by t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he BBC to introduce any significant or new technical solutions without the involvement of the wider industry. Significant investment went into developing the technology behind IPlayer from scratch. At some point in the future, an IPlayer refresh may take p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lace in order to make the service and contents more relevant and user friendly.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.4 Faced with the future option of developing new technology or buying a solution off the shelf from an established digital company, Pact would welcome the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">taking the oppo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rtunity to partner with digital companies and use expertise and solutions that are already being developed, to save investment costs where possible.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.5 The Charter allows for development in new technology platforms and we would want to see this provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> continue into the future, preferably as already articulated, investing in solutions already being developed. Pact also recognises, as does the BBC, that further work will need to be done working with digital companies to integrate the BBC’s service offeri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng with existing and future social media platforms.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.6 In terms of digital identifiers, the BBC should move quickly to introduce digital identifiers for content. The BBC’s Digital Media Initiative failed earlier in the year after £100m was invested into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the project. Digital identifiers in the form of ISAN (the international audio visual standard) have already been developed by the industry. BBC should look into integrating and using this international standard for registering audio visual works rather tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n going down an alternative route.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Funding beyond 2016</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">How should the BBC be funded beyond 2016? Is there a case for distributing funding for public service content more widely beyond the BBC? What comparisons can be made with the provision of public serv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ice content in other countries? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1 Pact is strong supporter of the BBC licence fee; this is essential for the delivery of quality broadcasting in the future and should be protected. The licence fee which is channelled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> into BBC programming also acts as seed funding driving the creation of British intellectual property. The licence fee gives the UK a competitive advantage and a platform into international markets, creating and sustaining thousands of jobs in the process.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2 The BBC is the envy of public broadcasters around the world and a recent report</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> underlines the value of the BBC in creating and selling Britain’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘soft power’ overseas. The report demonstrated that cultural factors such as language, creativity and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">values contribute to the UK’s attractiveness as a source of overseas trade and investment and that:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">People who consume BBC services more frequently have more favourable perceptions of the UK</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.5pt; text-indent:-16.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The more business leaders know and consume the BBC, the more like</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly they are to trade with the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3 The success of the current regime is demonstrated in the fact that TV exports have more than doubled over the last few years. The most recent Pact/UKTI Export report shows that UK TV exports continue to rise and were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">up 4% overall to £1,178m in 2012. The main markets are the US and Europe but with strong growth in China </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(+90%), Indonesia (+81%) and India (+42%) and future potential in other markets also.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.4 In terms of funding beyond 2016, Pact would support an approp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">riate annual increment to the licence fee. This may be in line with, or higher than, inflation taking into account the changing economic environment. Pact would be concerned that a failure to secure future funding for the BBC would erode the budget for fut</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ure original content which is a driver of IP creation.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.5 Pact is opposed to any redistribution of the licence fee to other broadcasters. The BBC has integrated the licence fee into its business plan and operating model and demonstrated that it can creat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e, deliver and sustain high quality content over a period of time. By redistributing this fee to other broadcasters, the current impact of the Public Service Broadcaster would be lost.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.6 Competition amongst the broadcasters is important to drive creativ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ity and innovation. By replacing the licence fee with advertising revenue in any way would damage the BBC’s unique service model. The BBC drives the world’s best TV industry which is vastly different from similar sized countries such as Italy with RaiUno. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The competition angle is important in sustaining future success in the sector.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Governance, Regulation and accountability</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">How should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secret</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ary of State, together, provide the most appropriate constitutional framework for the BBC?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.1 Pact agrees that there should continue to be an appropriate governance structure that holds the BBC management to account. A ten year Charter that provides conti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nuity and a strategic view, agreed by the Government, is still the most appropriate constitutional framework.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Pact Census Independent Production Sector Financial Census and Survey 2013, by Oliver &amp; Ohlbaum Associates Ltd (June 2013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Pact Census Independent Production Sector Financial Census and Survey 2013, by Oliver &amp; Ohlbaum Associates Limited (June 2013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a